### Steps to reproduce

The `Test-ModuleManifest` cmdlet doesn't return an updated manifest if the .psd1 file gets updated. Here's a Pester 5 test case that reproduces the issue. I've reproduced on Windows PowerShell 5.1 and PowerShell 7.2.0. 

```powershell

Import-Module -Name 'Pester' -MinimumVersion '5.0'

Describe 'Test-ModuleManifest.when manifest changes' {
    It 'should reload manifest' {
        $testRoot = $TestDrive
        $psm1Path = Join-Path -Path $TestDrive -ChildPath 'MyModule.psm1'
        New-Item -Path $psm1Path -ItemType 'File'
        
        $psd1Path = Join-Path -Path $TestDrive -ChildPath 'MyModule.psd1'
        @"
@{
    RootModule = 'MyModule.psm1';
    Description = 'MyModule';
    Author = 'ajensen';
    ModuleVersion = '1.2.3';
    PrivateData = @{
        PSData = @{
            Prerelease = '';
        }
    }
}
"@ | Set-Content -Path $psd1Path
        
        $manifest = Test-ModuleManifest -Path $psd1Path
        $manifest.PrivateData['PSData']['Prerelease'] | Should -BeNullOrEmpty
        
        @"
@{
    RootModule = 'MyModule.psm1';
    Description = 'MyModule';
    Author = 'ajensen';
    ModuleVersion = '1.2.3';
    PrivateData = @{
        PSData = @{
            Prerelease = 'beta1';
        }
    }
}
"@ | Set-Content -Path $psd1Path
        $manifest = Test-ModuleManifest -Path $psd1Path
        $manifest.PrivateData['PSData']['Prerelease'] | Should -Be 'beta1'
    }
}
```

### Expected behavior

```console
I expect `Test-ModuleManifest` to not cache the results of previous calls, or if it does, update its cache if the .psd1 file changes.
```


### Actual behavior

```console
`Test-ModuleManifest` returns the result of the last call no matter what changes you make to a module's .psd1 file.
```


